<LegalPage
  title="Privacy"
  eyebrow="Privacy · Last updated 21 July 2026"
  description="Somnary's privacy policy. We collect as little as possible: no data selling, no ad-tracking, and most of the site works without collecting anything that identifies you."
  lastUpdated="21 July 2026"
>
  <p class="lead">
    Somnary is built to need as little of your data as possible. This policy explains what we
    collect, why, and your rights. It’s written to align with the Australian Privacy Act 1988
    (and the Australian Privacy Principles) and, for visitors in the EU/UK, the GDPR.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>The short version:</strong> we don’t sell your data, we don’t run ad-tracking, and
    most of the site works without collecting anything that identifies you.
  </p>

  <h2>1. What we collect</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Newsletter (the dispatch):</strong> the dispatch newsletter isn’t publishing yet, but
      you can leave your email to be told when it launches. If you do, we store just that email
      address (in our database, hosted by Supabase — see “sharing” below), only to send you a note
      when the dispatch starts. Nothing else, no spam, and you can ask us to remove it any time.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Claim / label submissions:</strong> if you send us a sleep claim or a product label
      to check, we store what you submit (and your email only if you choose to add one) to help us
      decide what to research and to run the correction process. These are also stored in our
      Supabase database. Please don’t include personal health details — we don’t need them and ask
      you not to send them.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Analytics:</strong> we currently run no analytics: no third-party scripts, no
      cookies, no cross-site tracking, and no profile of you. If we add analytics later, it will
      be a privacy-respecting, cookieless tool (such as Plausible or Fathom) that measures only
      aggregate traffic, and we’ll update this policy before turning it on.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Search queries:</strong> sitewide search isn’t live yet. When it is, searches you
      run may be logged in aggregate, anonymised form to help us decide what to research and
      cover next. We won’t tie searches to your identity.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Community reports (when launched):</strong> these are anonymous by design: no
      name, no email, no account — and they stay separate and pseudonymous even if you are signed in
      (a report is never linked to your account). Don’t include anything in a report that could
      identify you; we don’t want it and don’t store it.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Corrections / emails:</strong> if you email us, we keep your message and address to
      reply and to track the correction.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Accounts (optional):</strong> you don’t need an account to use Somnary — every page, its
      sources, search, and the whole guide work signed-out. An account does one thing: it lets you
      save a reading map from the guide so you can return to it. If you create one (through Google
      sign-in or an email “magic link”, handled by Supabase Auth), we store your account identifier and
      the email address you sign in with. For each map you choose to save, we store the structured
      answers you selected in the guide (the sleep problems, how often, the age band, and the evening
      habits you picked) <em>and</em> the remedy names you typed when we asked what you’d tried, plus
      the reading map itself (the links) and any habits-checklist ticks. We do <strong>not</strong>
      store a free-text transcript of your conversation — the free-text notes you type are dropped
      before anything is saved; only the fixed answers you selected and the remedy names you mentioned
      are kept. You can view and delete your saved maps yourself, any time, at{' '}
      <a href="/account">your account page</a>; deleting a map removes it from our database. There is
      no login wall.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>AI features (“ask this page”, the “Ask Somnary” search answer, and the guide):</strong>
      when you use one of the optional AI features, the text you send (your question, or the answers
      you type into the guide) is sent to a third-party AI service — OpenRouter, which routes it to a
      DeepSeek model, or Google’s Gemini API as a fallback — to generate the answer. We don’t attach
      your name or email, and we don’t log what you type to build a profile of you. The provider
      processes the request as our AI provider under its API terms. Because your text leaves our
      servers to reach the provider, please don’t type anything that identifies you or that you
      consider sensitive. These features are optional: every page, its sources, and the reading the
      guide points to all work without them, and the guide keeps nothing after it answers — unless you
      are signed in and choose “save this map”, which stores only the structured result described under
      “Accounts (optional)” above (never the AI text you sent).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Somnary Lens research counts:</strong> when the Lens researches a supplement or
      ingredient, we keep an <strong>aggregate count</strong> of which <em>named</em> products and
      ingredients people look up, so we can decide what to grade next. We store <strong>only the
      normalised name and a running count</strong> — for example, “ashwagandha: 42”. We do
      <strong>not</strong> store the free-text questions you type into the Lens; we don’t log a run when
      the Lens declines to research (an off-topic, safety, or dosing question) or when it just points you
      to a page we’ve already graded; we don’t store the pasted text of a supplement-facts label (only a
      recognised ingredient name from it); and we don’t tie a Lens run to your identity, your IP, or keep
      any per-search record. It is a tally of subjects, nothing more.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>2. What we don’t do</h2>
  <p>
    No selling or renting of personal data. No advertising networks. No affiliate or vendor
    tracking pixels. No selling of search or interest data. Ever. It’s core to what Somnary is.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Why we can use your data (legal bases, for GDPR readers)</h2>
  <p>
    Newsletter: your consent. Anonymised analytics/search: our legitimate interest in running and
    improving the site. Emails: to respond to you.
  </p>

  <h2>4. Cookies</h2>
  <p>
    The site runs without tracking cookies, and we don’t currently set any non-essential cookies.
    If that ever changes for EU/UK visitors, we’ll add a consent banner before turning any such
    cookie on.
  </p>

  <h2>5. Sharing</h2>
  <p>
    We share data with the service providers that run the site for us: our host, Vercel; Supabase,
    which stores the email addresses and claim/label submissions described above, and — if you create
    one — your optional account (Supabase Auth handles Google/email-link sign-in) and the reading maps
    you save (its servers are the database behind those forms and accounts); and — only when you use
    one of the optional AI features — our
    AI provider OpenRouter (which routes your text to a DeepSeek model), or Google’s Gemini API as a
    fallback, which processes the text you sent to generate the answer. If we add an email-sending
    tool (for the dispatch) or analytics, we’ll name them here too. Each is bound to handle data for
    us alone. We may disclose information if required by law.
  </p>

  <h2>6. Retention</h2>
  <p>
    Newsletter emails until you ask us to remove you (before launch, that removal is manual, by
    email); claim/label submissions for as long as they inform our research and the correction log;
    account and saved maps until you delete them (each map is deletable by you at any time on{' '}
    <a href="/account">your account page</a>, and you can ask us to remove the whole account); emails
    for as long as needed to handle your query; analytics in aggregate only.
  </p>

  <h2>7. Your rights</h2>
  <p>
    You can ask us to access, correct, or delete the personal data we hold about you (essentially
    just your email, if you’ve subscribed or written to us, plus your account and saved maps if you’ve
    created an account), and you can unsubscribe at any time. If you have an account, you can view and
    delete your saved maps yourself at <a href="/account">your account page</a> without contacting us.
    EU/UK readers also have GDPR rights including objection and portability. To exercise any of
    these, email <a href="mailto:sammymoz@gmail.com">sammymoz@gmail.com</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>8. Data location</h2>
  <p>
    Our service providers may store data outside Australia. Our host, Vercel, and our database
    provider, Supabase, operate globally and may process data in the United States, and our AI
    provider — OpenRouter/DeepSeek, or Google’s Gemini API as a fallback, used only for the optional
    AI features — may likewise process the text you sent in the United States or elsewhere. We choose
    providers with appropriate safeguards.
  </p>

  <h2>9. Children</h2>
  <p>
    The site isn’t directed at children, and we don’t knowingly collect their data.
  </p>

  <h2>10. Complaints</h2>
  <p>
    If you’re in Australia and think we’ve mishandled your data, you can complain to us first at
    <a href="mailto:sammymoz@gmail.com">sammymoz@gmail.com</a>, and then to the Office of the
    Australian Information Commissioner (OAIC). EU/UK readers may complain to their local
    data-protection authority.
  </p>

  <h2>11. Changes</h2>
  <p>We’ll update the “last updated” date when this policy changes.</p>
</LegalPage>
